{
  "doc_id": "56212",
  "text": "EDCs undergo significant bioaccumulation [CITATION_1] , and various forms of metabolites can be detected in plasma and urine samples, the levels of which have served as a reference for estimating the levels of exposure. In a survey of subjects in New Zealand, [CITATION_2] reported the plasma concentration of alkyl phenol of about 0.32 µg/L, which is between 10 -9 M and 10 -8 M. Also, in a study of 394 adults in the United States, [CITATION_3] detected NP in 51% of samples, with levels ≥ 0.1 µg/L; the median and 95th percentile concentrations were < 0.1 µg/L and 1.57 µg/L, respectively. In the present study, the effective concentrations of NP and 4-OP for modulation of TNF-α expression were within the range of estimated exposure levels.",
